I was getting ready to do what I love to do - dance - at “￼Holiday in the Tre”, when this a little girl I don’t know comes up to me and says, can I dance with you? What was that supposed to say, is Christmas time, so what did I do? I scooped her up and danced with her. It was ￼such a sweet moment. She smiled from ear to ear. I ended up meeting her grandmother and she told me that this little girl loves to dance but normally does not engage with people. I’m glad I made her smile. That’s what Christmas at Emancipation Park is all about: putting smiles on kids’ faces. Note: I did not miss a beat on that line dance! ￼

I’m saddened to hear of the death of Council Member/activist Ada Edwards. She was my councilmember. ￼I’m extremely grateful and thankful that I had the opportunity to know her. She is one of the reasons that I am in politics. She appointed me to the LARA ￼Board for the City of Houston. She knew that affordable housing was extremely important to me, after my failed run for Houston City Council in 2003. She appointment me in 2004. She asked me to challenge the authority of Mayor Bill White and make sure that I asked the right questions to make sure that the money meant to help make homes affordable be directed to the homes and not the developers. I followed her instructions and asked the tough questions. Mayor White then threatened to remove me from the LARA Board. The funny thing is when I spoke with CM Edwards about that she told me, and I quote, “Bill White  didn’t put you on the board and he can’t take you off. I did. You keep doing exactly what you’re doing, and I dare him to do something to you!” For the record, I stayed on that board until I ran, and won the At-Large 5￼ City Council seat in 2007. She was a baddie before baddies were thing! She was unapologetically a fighter for the people! She taught disenfranchise people how to stand up to those in power. She was unafraid and was a great role model for me! I will miss you, Councilmember Edwards, but your legacy lives on! My thoughts and prayers go to her family, including Todd.

Coach Doolittle is a prime example of how important coaches are in young people’s lives. I love you, Coach!

I still feel some kind away about those two extra years of literal enslavement! We are losing rights, Black people, left, and right! Bills passed out of the Texas state house in the Texas senate that outlawed the practice of diversity, equity and inclusion in public education! And the governor signed into law! This means that we can’t even teach about Juneteenth in schools in Texas that receive public dollars! We are not truly free! If you really want to ensure that we are free, in every way possible, then vote for people who believe in our true emancipation!

If you’re poor and you’re struggling to make ends meet or you can’t afford groceries or you don’t have furniture or you don’t have Christmas for your kids, I would invite you to visit the Joseph House. You name it. They have it. They even have shopping baskets to help you put on your FREE stuff into. I’m really impressed. Had the opportunity to visit them today. #CharityMatters #communitymatters

4 the record, I’m a hard “NO” on vouchers! So, history shows us that we should expect our children will NOT ￼be admitted into these prestigious private schools that cost well more than $8k (voucher amount) but instead be admitted into some newly-minted-former-“charter”-school-now turned-“private”-pop-up-religious-or-neighborhood-school for the very low 🥴price of $7,999.00, just in time to accept your 8k voucher, with well-intentioned, or maybe not, (crooks looking for $￼8K a pop) non-certified staff, 😳 where they will either under or not educate our children! Oh, and now we must find transportation for our children to get to and from school and come up with breakfast & lunch money! Trust me, there will be no extracurricular activities for our children or sports, so bye-bye Friday night lights and volleyball and the other sports! And, please don’t let our children have disabilities, they assuredly won’t ￼be accommodated! I’m a Hard NO! Vouchers were created in an effort to STOP integration! The “Choice” was the choice of parents to take their children out of schools with Black kids. That movement has evolved into this 2023 version. Know history or we’re doomed to repeat it! Read the 1956 Report that was issued in response to Brown v. Board and why the original Texas voucher bill was created. They used the term “parent choice” so parent’s could feel empowered to avoid and fight integration. They even hung a dummy of a black man at Mansfield HS in Texas to scare Blacks from trying to integrate. As I listen to the arguments on the amendment to the amendment to Amendment #2 of SB1. After all of the arguments, I will PROUDLY vote YES on this amendment! ESAs must go! #NoVoucherScams #NoWelfareForTheRich Voucher scams are on the floor of the Texas House today. These scams defund our public schools and give our taxpayer dollars to unaccountable private schools. I will never vote for a voucher scam. #txlege • I’m grinding all my life for the adequate funding of public schools in Texas. #NoEntitlements

I had the honor today of attending the groundbreaking partnership between the Houston Airport System and the Texas Southern University School of Aviation. In attendance were diversity at its best! One of the standout people that I met was a young lady who graduated from Sterling HS. While there and because there was an aviation club there decided to join. Her interest was peaked. She knew she wanted to be a pilot. She piloted her first flight in high school, in southeast, Houston. She then attended and graduated from the Texas Southern University School of Aviation. She now makes a good living doing what she loves: FLYING PLANES! She’s not a commercial pilot. She’s a private pilot! She flies superstars wherever they wanna go! I am super impressed with this young lady. What inspired me the most was is that I fly a lot and most pilots I see or white males. Every now and then I’ll see your white female pilot and even rarer I may see a black male pilot. I don’t know if I’ve ever seen a black female pilot in all my years of flying. Knowing that she’s a pilot warmed my heart! Black girls you can grow up to be pilots! She is a #BadA$$! And I mean that! World, please meet @pilot.tahti 🛫🛬✈️🛩️‼️❗️#BlackAndEducated #BlackGirlMagic #BlackGreatness
